  "texts": [
    "R-forth) for g • f is obvious.",
    "To show that g • f satisfies ⊑-back, we must show that if y H ⊑ H g(f (x)), then there is a y F ∈ F such that y F ⊑ F x and g(f (y F)) ⊑ H y H. So suppose y H ⊑ H g(f (x)).",
    "Then by ⊑-back for g, there is a y G ∈ G such that y G ⊑ G f (x) and g(y G) ⊑ H y H. Given y G ⊑ G f (x) and ⊑-back for f, there is a y F ∈ F such that y F ⊑ F x and f (y F) ⊑ G y G. By ⊑- forth for g, f (y F) ⊑ G y G implies g(f (y F)) ⊑ H g(y G), which with g(y G) ⊑ H y H implies g(f (y F)) ⊑ H y H, which with y F ⊑ F x means that y F is our desired witness.",
    "Next, to show that g•f satisfies R-back, we must show that if g(f (x))R H i y H and z H ⊑ H y H, then there is a y F ∈ F such that xR F i y F and g(f (y F)) ≬ H z H. So suppose g(f (x))R H i y H and z H ⊑ H y H. Then by R-back for g, there is y G ∈ G such that f (x)R G i y G and g(y G) ≬ H z H. Since g(y G) ≬ H z H, there is a u H ∈ H such that u H ⊑ H g(y G) and u H ⊑ H z H. By ⊑-back for g, u H ⊑ H g(y G) implies that there is a u G ∈ G such that u G ⊑ G y G and g(u G) ⊑ H u H. Given f (x)R G i y G and u G ⊑ G y G, R-back for f implies that there is a y F ∈ F such that xR F i y F and f (y F) ≬ G u G. Thus, there is a v G ∈ G such that v G ⊑ G f (y F) and v G ⊑ G u G, which with ⊑-forth for g implies g(v G) ⊑ H g(f (y F)) and g(v G) ⊑ H g(u G), which with g(u G) ⊑ H u H ⊑ H z H from above gives us g(f (y F)) ≬ H z H. This completes the proof of part 2.Part 3 is well known.The importance of Fact 3.9 is that it allows us to think in categorical terms as follows.Remark 3.10 (Categories).",
